<h2>I. Why This Question Suddenly Matters More</h2>

<p>The question "How do you tell if someone's thinking is above your own?" has been a perennial favorite on Chinese Q&A platform Zhihu. But in 2026, it carries a new subtext.</p>

<p>Because by now, LLMs have passed the bar exam, beaten doctors on medical licensing, and solved PhD-level mathematics. If "higher cognition" simply means "knowing more and reasoning better," then by 2026, an LLM has higher cognition than 99% of humans. And yet, none of us would say AI is "cognitively above" Einstein — even if it can recite every one of his papers.</p>

<p><strong>The premise of the question is being rewritten: the criteria we used to judge cognitive superiority — knowledge breadth, logical agility, reaction speed — are precisely the things AI is now best at.</strong></p>

<h2>II. The Three Blind Spots of Traditional Answers</h2>

<p>Before AI, the highest-voted answers to this question clustered around three criteria:</p>

<p><strong>Criterion One: "Whether someone can admit they don't know."</strong> (The Dunning-Kruger effect: low performers overestimate themselves.)</p>

<p><strong>Criterion Two: "Whether someone can view problems from different angles."</strong> (Cognitive flexibility.)</p>

<p><strong>Criterion Three: "Whether someone can quickly grasp the essence."</strong> (Abstract reasoning.)</p>

<p>All three made sense in the pre-AI era. But in 2026, each has a blind spot:</p>

<p><strong>Blind Spot for Criterion One</strong> — LLMs, when asked "Are you sure?", display calibrated self-doubt. A <em>Frontiers</em> study (2025) found that ChatGPT's metacognitive calibration in confidence judgments is more "rational" than the average human. "Knowing what you don't know" is something AI now does better than you.</p>

<p><strong>Blind Spot for Criterion Two</strong> — AI is, by design, a system that simultaneously views problems from every angle. Ask it to analyze a business decision, and it can output Porter's Five Forces, SWOT, Blue Ocean, game theory, and systems dynamics — all at once. "Cognitive flexibility" is one of AI's strongest capabilities.</p>

<p><strong>Blind Spot for Criterion Three</strong> — Distilling the core insight from large volumes of text is precisely what LLMs were built for. The <em>New York Times</em> (April 2026) noted that AI can perform in seconds what takes humans hours of information distillation.</p>

<p><strong>So here's the question: if someone knows more than you, is better at admitting ignorance, has wider perspective, and grasps essence faster — and that someone is AI — would you say they are cognitively above you?</strong></p>

<p>Most people's intuitive answer is "no." Why?</p>

<h2>III. A Four-Layer Model of Cognition</h2>

<p>My answer: <strong>Human cognition is not linear. It is layered. AI dominates the bottom layers; humans retain an edge in the upper layers — and the rules there are entirely different.</strong></p>

<pre>
┌────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 4: Value Judgment          │ ← Human's ultimate moat
│  "What's worth asking about?"     │
├────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 3: Question Asking         │ ← Human advantage emerges
│  "What to ask?"                   │
├────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 2: Logical Processing      │ ← AI dominates
│  "How to analyze?"                │
├────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 1: Knowledge Storage       │ ← AI dominates
│  "What do you know?"             │
└────────────────────────────────────┘
</pre>

<h3>Layer 1: Knowledge Storage</h3>

<p>The standard of the industrial age. The more someone read, experienced, and accumulated, the "higher" their cognition. In the pre-AI era, this was reasonable — knowledge itself was scarce.</p>

<p><strong>In 2025, a $30/month subscription unlocks all of human civilization's knowledge.</strong> If you're still judging cognitive level by "how much this person knows," you're comparing horse speed in the age of trains.</p>

<h3>Layer 2: Logical Processing</h3>

<p>The standard of the information age. Who can analyze problems faster, build causal chains, identify logical fallacies, and think structurally.</p>

<p><strong>GPT-5's logical reasoning already exceeds the average human level.</strong> As Johan Roos concluded in <em>Forbes</em> (Nov 2025): "AI is unmatched in efficiency, speed, and consistency — but efficiency is not wisdom."</p>

<h3>Layer 3: Question Asking</h3>

<p>This is where humans begin to build a real advantage. McKinsey's 2026 leadership reports repeatedly highlight one concept: <strong>"In the AI era, the ability to ask the right question is scarcer than the ability to find the right answer"</strong> (McKinsey, 2026). The WEF's 2026 Global Skills Report ranks "questioning ability" as the most undervalued workplace capability of the AI era.</p>

<p>To judge whether someone's thinking is above yours: don't look at how well they answer — <strong>look at whether they ask questions you never thought of, but that immediately strike you as "we should be asking that."</strong></p>

<p>Example: In a business strategy meeting, everyone is focused on how to use AI to cut costs. The cognitively higher person doesn't join that discussion. Instead, they ask: <strong>"What if we use AI not to cut costs, but to create costs — to offer entirely new services that were previously too expensive to build?"</strong></p>

<p>That question replaces the core assumption of the entire meeting.</p>

<h3>Layer 4: Value Judgment</h3>

<p>The highest layer. <strong>"What's worth asking" is a dimension above "how to ask."</strong></p>

<p>AI can generate 100 relevant questions. But which one is the most important, right now, to pursue? This requires: ethical judgment, aesthetic preference, risk appetite, trade-offs between short and long term, understanding of impact on self and others — <strong>all things AI does not (yet) have.</strong></p>

<p>The ultimate criteria for judging whether someone's thinking is above yours:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>What problems they choose to spend time on</strong> — this reveals their values</li>
  <li><strong>Their tolerance for uncertainty</strong> — cognitively advanced people hold contradictory positions without needing binary answers</li>
  <li><strong>Their decision quality when there is no correct answer</strong> — it's not about "what's right," it's about "how to frame the choice"</li>
</ol>

<p>A 2025 study published via <em>PsyPost</em> found: <strong>the most frequent users of generative AI are the least accurate in assessing their own competence with AI</strong> — meaning "overconfidence" exists not just between human and human, but between human and machine. The cognitively advanced person is precisely the one who <strong>knows why they are limited</strong>.</p>

<h2>IV. Three Practical Tests</h2>

<h3>Test One: Do they rush to answer before defining the problem?</h3>

<p>Low cognition: You're mid-sentence and they're already prescribing solutions.<br>
<strong>High cognition: They pause and ask — "Wait, are we sure we're discussing the same problem?"</strong></p>

<p>In the AI era, the ability to provide solutions is rapidly commoditizing. The ability to <strong>define the problem</strong> is rapidly appreciating.</p>

<h3>Test Two: Can they explain complex ideas to someone with less context?</h3>

<p>Cognitively advanced people share a trait: <strong>they can communicate downward — they re-frame a complex logic in someone else's knowledge framework.</strong></p>

<p>This isn't condescension; it's the luxury of cognitive security. People who aren't cognitively secure use jargon and complexity to create information asymmetry — because it's their only way of seeming "above" others.</p>

<h3>Test Three: Are they comfortable saying "I don't know" — really?</h3>

<p>Not "I don't know but I'll pretend," and not "I don't know but I can learn." But: <strong>"This is outside my cognitive range. I can't even classify what domain this belongs to."</strong></p>

<p><strong>When someone can calmly admit they are not even at the stage of "uncertainty" about something, it shows a clear perception of their own cognitive boundaries.</strong> That is genuine metacognition.</p>

<h2>V. What "Higher Cognition" Means in the AI Era</h2>

<p>When AI has seized absolute dominance over the bottom two layers, the standard for judging cognitive level shifts from "how many questions can you answer" to <strong>"which questions do you choose to answer."</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>Memory doesn't matter — AI is your external brain</li>
  <li>Analysis doesn't matter — AI is your analysis assistant</li>
  <li>Logical deduction doesn't matter — AI runs all the paths for you</li>
</ul>

<p>What remains, what cannot be replaced, what is worth using as the benchmark for "higher cognition," is a person's ability to <strong>identify which questions are important vs. unimportant — and the courage to act on that identification.</strong></p>

<p><strong>So how do you tell if someone's thinking is above yours?</strong></p>

<p><strong>They have given up doing what AI can do. They spend all their time on what AI cannot do. And you had never even considered that those things could be left undone.</strong></p>

<hr class="article-divider">

<p><em>📍 humanaifit insight: Our core belief — real competitive advantage comes not from AI itself, but from the collaborative growth of human intelligence and artificial intelligence. In this framework, the standard for "higher cognition" is no longer "is this person better than AI." It is: through what value framework, and by what process, do they choose which questions are worth humans and AI thinking about together?</em></p>

